Kendall,

The Parameters runner and Theories runner are built to handle
different scenarios.  With a Theory, you&#39;re building a Universal
Truth; you&#39;re stating &quot;this holds for any possible parameters (that
meet my assumptions).  Here are some example parameters.&quot;  With a
Parameters method, you&#39;re building an Answer Key; you&#39;re saying &quot;this
holds for these values exactly, and possibly others, but I make no
promises.&quot;  Are you building an Answer Key, or stating a Universal
Truth?

That said, from a practical point of view, the ease of using each
runner depends on how you want to specify your data--I hope that this
limitation will lessen in future releases.  Where are your 200 strings
coming from?  Thanks,

   David Saff

On 10/20/07, Kendall Shaw &lt;queshaw@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; The popper tutorial that the junit 4.4 release notes refers to shows
&gt; an example of a parameter supplier, which allows data points for
&gt; theories to come from parameters of an annotation:
&gt;
&gt; http://popper.tigris.org/tutorial.html
&gt;
&gt; The example allows you to use the parameters of an annotation as
&gt; parameters for the theory:
&gt;
&gt; @Theory public void multiplyIsInverseOfDivideWithInlineDataPoints(
&gt;      @Between(first=-100, last=100) int amount,
&gt;      @Between(first=-100, last=100) int m
&gt;    ) {
&gt;      assumeThat(m, not(0));
&gt;      assertThat(new Dollar(amount).times(m).divideBy(m).getAmount(),
&gt;          is(amount));
&gt;    }
&gt;
&gt; I think the parameters first and last have to be compile time
&gt; constants, is that right? How can I I test with parameters that
&gt; aren&#39;t constants? I wouldn&#39;t want to put 200 strings in the parameter
&gt; list, for example. I could use integers like the Between annotation
&gt; above, as indices into an array or function I guess.
&gt;
&gt; I used the @Parameters JUnit annotation instead for a test. From what
&gt; I see so far, that looks to me like a simpler solution in general,
&gt; than using @Theory. Is that right?
